    faqs: [
      { question: "Can solo attorneys realistically compete for Google rankings?", answer: "Yes - with the right strategy. Competing for hyper-specific, local, practice-area terms is very achievable for solo attorneys with consistent SEO work. The Launchpad plan is specifically designed for attorneys in this position." },
    ],
    extendedFaqs: [
      { question: "What is the most important marketing investment for a solo attorney?", answer: "A professional website and a fully optimized Google Business Profile - in that order. The website is your credibility anchor for every referral and first impression. Every warm referral, every person who finds your name on a local bar directory, and every former client who refers a friend will Google you before calling. The GBP is your fastest path to appearing in local searches for your practice area without waiting months for organic SEO to compound. Together they form the foundation that every other marketing activity builds on. Both are included in the Launchpad package." },
      { question: "How do solo attorneys compete with large law firms in SEO?", answer: "By targeting specific niches and geographic sub-markets where large firms have not optimized. A 20-attorney firm targets \'divorce lawyer Dallas\'. A well-positioned solo attorney can own \'divorce lawyer Frisco TX\' or \'divorce attorney McKinney TX\' - cities within the same metro where the large firm has no specific presence and where monthly search volume is still substantial. Searches like \'DUI attorney Tempe\', \'immigration lawyer Glendale AZ\', or \'workers comp attorney Pasadena CA\' all have real search volume and far less competitive pressure than the metro head terms. Specificity and locality are the solo attorney\'s primary SEO advantages, and they are more achievable in a shorter time frame than broad competition." },
      { question: "How much should a solo attorney budget for marketing?", answer: "Most solo attorneys see meaningful results starting at $2,000 per month. The Launchpad plan starts at $2,000/month and covers your website, GBP optimization, and foundational local SEO - the three highest-ROI channels for a solo practice. Solo attorneys who invest consistently at this level for 6 months typically see a positive return, because one additional case per month from marketing usually covers the investment. We do not recommend engaging at less than $2,000/month on legal marketing if you want results that actually move your practice forward. Below that threshold, the work that can be done is not enough to generate consistent momentum." },
      { question: "How important is a personal brand for solo attorneys?", answer: "It is one of your most important differentiators, and most solo attorneys underinvest in it. Solo attorneys who communicate their story - why they practice this area of law, what drives their approach, the types of cases they have handled - consistently outperform solo attorneys who present as generic law offices. A strong attorney bio page with a professional photo, a genuine first-person voice, and specific case experience described in plain language is one of the highest-ROI pages on a solo attorney\'s website. When a prospective client is comparing three attorneys, the one whose bio reads as a real person with a clear point of view on their practice gets the call." },
      { question: "Do solo attorneys need to be active on social media?", answer: "For most consumer-facing practice areas - criminal defense, family law, personal injury, immigration - no. Google and your GBP are where clients search, and that is where your marketing attention should be concentrated. Social media is low-priority for solo attorneys compared to SEO, GBP optimization, and review generation. The exception is estate planning and business law practices where LinkedIn visibility genuinely helps with referral source relationships. But if your choice is between posting on Instagram three times a week and asking one more client for a Google review after each case closes, the review wins every time." },
      { question: "How do reviews help solo attorneys compete against bigger firms?", answer: "Reviews are the most direct way a solo attorney can close the trust gap with larger firms. A solo attorney with 45 Google reviews averaging 4.9 stars, where multiple reviews mention \'worked directly with the attorney from start to finish\', will regularly outperform a 10-attorney firm with 20 reviews in both map pack rankings and conversion rate. Clients read reviews carefully in practice areas where they are making a high-stakes personal decision - family law, DUI, immigration - and the specific language in the review text does persuasion work. Build a simple post-case email that requests a review and sends automatically 10 to 14 days after case closure. Doing this consistently for one year produces a review profile that becomes a genuine competitive asset." },
      { question: "What should a solo attorney\'s website focus on?", answer: "Three things: who you are, what specific cases you handle, and how to contact you. The attorney bio should be prominent and personal - not a bulleted credential list. The practice area pages should be organized by specific case type, not by broad category, and each page should speak to the client\'s specific situation and the outcomes they care about. The contact mechanism should be visible on every page without scrolling, and the form should ask for name, phone, and a one-line description of the situation - not a paragraph essay. The goal of the website is to answer \'is this the right attorney for my case?\' and make it easy to take the next step." },
      { question: "How long does it take solo attorney SEO to produce results?", answer: "For sub-metro and neighborhood-level keyword targets - \'DUI attorney Scottsdale\', \'family law attorney Lakewood CO\', \'immigration lawyer Doral FL\' - most solo attorneys see their first page-one rankings within 4 to 6 months of a properly built and consistent campaign. GBP map pack appearances typically start within 8 to 12 weeks of a fully optimized profile with an active review generation program. Organic case leads - meaning prospective clients who found you through Google without being a referral - start arriving consistently at the 5 to 8 month mark for most markets. The return grows over time as domain authority accumulates and each new page ranks faster than the last." },
    ],
