    faqs: [
      { question: "How do workers' comp firms compete with insurance company marketing?", answer: "By owning educational content that answers worker questions before insurance adjusters frame the narrative. Informational SEO for 'what to do after a workplace injury' type queries is highly effective and low competition." },
    ],
    extendedFaqs: [
      { question: "What is the best way to market to injured workers who do not know they need an attorney?", answer: "Educational content is the primary tool. Workers who have just been injured and are navigating the claims process are searching for information: 'what to do after a workplace accident', 'how to file a workers comp claim', 'what does workers comp cover in [state]', 'can I see my own doctor for a work injury'. Content that answers these questions directly, and that explains the specific ways the insurance company's interests conflict with the worker's interests, moves people from information-gathering to considering representation. The most effective pages end with a specific call to action: 'Before you accept a settlement offer or sign anything from the insurance company, talk to a workers' comp attorney - the initial consultation is free.' This framing converts readers without feeling like a hard sell." },
      { question: "How competitive is workers comp SEO compared to personal injury?", answer: "Meaningfully less competitive in most markets. Workers' comp has consistent, year-round search volume - workplace injuries happen in every season, every industry, every zip code - but fewer law firms have invested in sophisticated SEO programs compared to PI. In most mid-size markets, a focused 6 to 9 month content and technical SEO program can reach first-page positions for workers' comp head terms with less investment than comparable PI terms would require. Industry-specific pages and Spanish-language content rank even faster because competition for those specific queries is sparse. The market opportunity in workers' comp SEO is real, and it is not yet as saturated as PI in most cities." },
      { question: "How important are reviews for workers comp attorneys, and what should they say?", answer: "Reviews are critical and the content of the reviews matters as much as the quantity. For workers' comp, the reviews that convert prospective clients most effectively are the ones that mention the insurance company specifically: 'They fought the insurance company when my claim was denied', 'The insurance adjuster was trying to lowball me and my attorney got me three times what they offered', 'I thought I had to accept whatever the insurance company said until I called this office'. These reviews speak directly to the fear and uncertainty that drives workers' comp clients to search for an attorney. We build review request workflows that prompt clients to describe their specific experience with the insurance dispute, which produces reviews that resonate far more than generic five-star feedback." },
      { question: "Should workers comp attorneys invest in television or billboard advertising?", answer: "TV and billboards build name recognition but are expensive, difficult to measure, and not targeted to people who are actively searching for help right now. For most workers' comp firms, the same budget invested in Google Ads, Local Service Ads, and SEO generates a better-tracked and lower cost-per-case result. We recommend digital-first for workers' comp marketing in almost all market sizes. The exception is a firm that has already saturated its digital channels - top map pack position, aggressive paid campaigns, strong organic rankings - and is looking for additional reach through traditional media. At that point, brand advertising in traditional channels can amplify the digital foundation you have already built." },
      { question: "Do workers comp firms need separate pages for different industries?", answer: "Yes, where case volume in a specific industry supports the investment. Construction site injury, healthcare worker injury, warehouse and logistics injury, transportation and trucking injury, and manufacturing injury are distinct search clusters with their own keyword patterns and their own client identity signals. A construction worker who fell off scaffolding identifies with being a construction worker, not with being a personal injury claimant. A page titled 'Construction Site Injury Workers Comp Attorney [City]' with content about OSHA violations, scaffold safety, third-party liability in addition to workers' comp, and the specific insurance dynamics on construction projects speaks directly to that client's situation. We research the actual search volume by industry in your specific market before deciding which industry pages to build." },
      { question: "How do workers comp attorneys build referral relationships with medical providers?", answer: "The most effective approach is consistent, professional outreach to the occupational medicine clinics, orthopedic practices, physical therapy groups, and urgent care centers in your service area - the providers who see injured workers first and most frequently. This means in-person visits, leaving branded materials that are genuinely useful to the provider (not just self-promotional), and following up on any cases where a provider has referred a patient so they know the outcome. Some workers' comp firms also produce educational content specifically for medical providers - guides on navigating the intersection of workers' comp and medical treatment, explanations of the attorney's role in disputes over medical authorization - that position the attorney as a resource rather than just a referral recipient. We help you build this outreach into a systematic program rather than an ad hoc effort." },
      { question: "What does a high-converting workers comp website look like?", answer: "A high-converting workers' comp site leads with the client's situation, not the attorney's credentials. Above the fold: a headline that speaks directly to injured workers ('Hurt at Work? The Insurance Company Has Lawyers. You Should Too.'), a prominent phone number with click-to-call for mobile, a one-sentence statement of the contingency fee arrangement, and a short contact form. The trust signals that convert best in workers' comp are reviews mentioning the insurance company and specific outcomes, a clear statement that the initial consultation is free and the attorney only gets paid if you win, and evidence of case results where state bar rules permit sharing them. Avoid lengthy biographies and legal jargon above the fold - injured workers on mobile do not read long paragraphs before deciding whether to call." },
    ],
    relatedServices: ["law-firm-seo", "local-seo-for-law-firms", "law-firm-content-writing"],
